            <div type="commentary">
                <p><emph>"For these I set no limits, world or time, But make a gift of empire without end."--Virgil, the Aenied</emph></p>
                <p>This base of a statue dedicated to A.P. Nepos Aponius Italicus Manilianus C. Licinius Pollio, an official under Trajan and Hadrian.  According to Werner Eck, he probably came from the Iberian peninsula and obtained the support of the Emperor Trajan for most of his career.<note>Eck, Werner. “Platorius”, in: Brill’s New Pauly, Antiquity volumes edited by: Hubert Cancik and, Helmuth Schneider, English Edition by: Christine F. Salazar, Classical Tradition volumes edited by: Manfred Landfester, English Edition by: Francis G. Gentry. <ref target="http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/brill-s-new-pauly/platorius-e927310">http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/brill-s-new-pauly/platorius-e927310</ref> (Accessed 07 April 2018).</note>  The statue itself was unearthed in Aquileia 1805, taken to Vienna in 1806, and returned to the Museo Archeologico in 1978.<note><bibl>Gordon, Arthur E. <ref target="https://tufts-primo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo-explore/fulldisplay?docid=01TUN_ALMA21107087550003851&amp;context=L&amp;vid=01TUN&amp;search_scope=EVERYTHING&amp;tab=everything&amp;lang=en_US"><emph>Illustrated Introduction to Latin Epigraphy.</emph></ref> Berkeley: University of California Press, 1983. P. 140.</bibl></note></p>
                <p>What makes this object particularly interesting is the number of places mentioned (no less than 8 geographic entities), providing a glimpse into the travels a Roman functionary made during the course of his career.
                During his life A.P. Nepos was stationed in Britain, Germany, Macedonia and Thrace, and montiored several main roads throughout Italy. This epigraph reveals the extent of the Roman Empire by the second century CE., and serves as a reminder of Jupiter's prophcecy from Aenid.</p>
                <p>Arthur Gordon suggestes that we read his titles in descending order<note><emph>Ibid.</emph></note>, so that we can trace a carerer starting as a member of the triumvir capitalis, then overseer of the viae Cassiae, Clodiae, Ciminiae novae, Traianae; legate of several legions, before wraping up his career as counsul of Britain, where he helped to construct Trajan's wall.<note>Eck, Werner.</note> </p>
                <p>This particular inscription is well documented with several translations available. I have attempted to render it fairly literally with an ear to modern sensibilites.</p>
